# [NEWPARTICIPANT](../wg/newparticipant.html)

## Summary

This session of the New Participant Program (NPP) focused on the creation, structure, and lifecycle of the primary work items of the IETF: Internet-Drafts (I-Ds) and Requests for Comments (RFCs). Presented by Alice Russo (RFC Production Center) and Rich Salz, the session provided newcomers with a practical guide to the tools, formats, publication streams, and standards processes required to write and publish documents in the IETF. The session concluded with an open Q&A addressing IANA interactions, the RFC update process, and methods for presenting new work to the community.

## Key Discussion Points

### Introduction to the RFC Series and Document Formats
* **RFC Definition and History**: Alice Russo explained that RFCs (Requests for Comments) are stable, permanent, and freely available documents designed to support internet interoperability. The RFC Editor website ([rfc-editor.org](https://www.rfc-editor.org)) was completely updated in May to improve accessibility and navigation.
* **Errata**: Because published RFCs cannot be modified, technical and editorial errors are tracked separately via the Errata portal ([errata.rfc-editor.org](https://errata.rfc-editor.org)).
* **Document Formats**:
  * **HTML**: The modern, responsive, and most accessible format. It supports SVG diagrams and displays metadata and Errata links on a right-hand sidebar.
  * **Plain Text**: The historical legacy format. Plain text files remain available, and older documents have been retrofitted with metadata and links via HTMLized views.
  * **PDF**: The only paginated format, which includes SVG diagrams.
  * **RFC XML**: The underlying XML-based vocabulary used as the source format for generating all other views. Authors typically do not write XML directly, opting instead for Markdown dialects.

### RFC Statuses, Subseries, and Streams
* **RFC Maturity Levels / Statuses**:
  * *Proposed Standard*: The entry point for standard-track specifications (~70% of publications).
  * *Internet Standard*: The final stage of standard-track maturity. The intermediate "Draft Standard" status is obsolete.
  * *Best Current Practice (BCP)*: Technical guidelines (e.g., OAuth 2.0 Security) or administrative processes (e.g., BCP 9).
  * *Informational / Experimental*: Non-standards track documents for use cases, frameworks, or time-limited experiments.
  * *Historic*: Superseded specifications (e.g., NTP v2).
  * *Unknown*: Applied to legacy documents published before formal statuses were defined (e.g., RFC 1).
* **Subseries (STDs and BCPs)**: Internet Standards and Best Current Practices are assigned subseries numbers (e.g., STD 7 for TCP). These numbers act as persistent containers; when an underlying RFC is obsoleted (such as TCP updating from RFC 793 to RFC 9293), the new RFC inherits the existing STD or BCP container number.
* **Publication Streams**:
  * *IETF Stream*: The only stream authorized to publish Standards Track or BCP documents.
  * *IAB Stream*: Internet Architecture Board workshop reports and architectural documents.
  * *IRTF Stream*: Research group outputs (not working group standards).
  * *Editorial Stream*: Policies and procedures governing the RFC series itself.
  * *Independent Submission Stream*: Open to submissions from the broader internet community that have not gone through an official IETF working group. It is managed by the Independent Submissions Editor (Eliot Lear).

### Anatomy and Writing of Internet-Drafts (I-Ds)
* **Internet-Draft Characteristics**: Rich Salz explained that I-Ds are temporary, evolving documents. They automatically expire after six months and are moved to an archive. Anyone can submit an I-D, and doing so permanently grants the IETF the right to modify and publish the material.
  * An extreme example of the open-submission policy is Warren Kumari’s humorous draft, `draft-kumari-not-a-standard` (which details a recipe for a peanut butter and jelly sandwich to demonstrate that any content can be submitted).
* **Authoring Toolchain**:
  * **Kramdown RFC** (developed by Carsten Bormann): A specialized Markdown dialect that understands RFC-specific formatting, front matter, and automated cross-referencing. This is the highly recommended tool for new authors.
  * **GitHub Integration**: Tools developed by volunteers (such as Martin Thomson) allow authors to manage drafts, collaborate, and automate submissions directly through GitHub.
  * **Author-Tools** (`authors.ietf.org`): The authoritative portal providing templates, schemas, and syntax validation (including the "nits" checker for ABNF, Yang, CDDL, and formatting errors).
* **Required Content**:
  * *Abstract & Introduction*: A concise summary (one paragraph) followed by an in-depth intro.
  * *Security Considerations*: A mandatory section explaining security implications, trade-offs, or stating why there is no security impact.
  * *IANA Considerations*: Mandatory section specifying any protocol numbers, ports, or registry allocations required from the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.
  * *References*: Split strictly into *Normative* (required to implement the spec) and *Informative* (additional helpful reading).
  * *Inclusive Language*: Authors must adhere to IETF and NIST-aligned guidelines on inclusive language (e.g., avoiding terms like master-slave, blacklist-whitelist).

### RFC Production and Publication Process
* **The Queue**: Once a working group and the IESG approve a draft, it enters the RFC Production Center queue.
* **Editorial Review**: Staff perform a light copy-edit to improve clarity and formatting. If a latent technical issue is uncovered, the document is referred back to the Area Director and Working Group.
* **Final Review (Auth48)**: Historically known as "Authors' 48 Hours" (though rarely lasting exactly 48 hours), this phase requires every listed author to review the copy-edited draft and provide explicit approval before final publication and assignment of an RFC number.

